        <tr><td>Tuesday</td><td>1,500–1,600 kcal, 120g+ protein</td><td>30 min walk</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Wednesday</td><td>1,500–1,600 kcal, 120g+ protein</td><td>Resistance training (45 min)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Thursday</td><td>1,500–1,600 kcal, 120g+ protein</td><td>Rest or light activity</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Friday</td><td>1,500–1,600 kcal, 120g+ protein</td><td>Resistance training (45 min)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Saturday</td><td>Flexible — stay within weekly average</td><td>Active leisure (hiking, sport)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Sunday</td><td>Flexible — stay within weekly average</td><td>Rest</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p style="font-size:.85rem;color:var(--ink3);margin-top:8px;">Calorie targets are illustrative. Use our <a href="calorie-calculator.html" style="color:var(--accent);">Calorie Calculator</a> to find your personal target.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="article-section">
    <h2>How Long Will It Actually Take?</h2>
    <p>At a sustainable 400–500 kcal daily deficit, expect to lose 5kg of fat in approximately 10–13 weeks. Add in normal weight fluctuations, the occasional higher-calorie week, and the adjustment periods, and a realistic expectation is 3–5 months to see 5kg of lasting fat loss reflected on the scale.</p>
    <p>This is slower than many diets promise. It is also the rate at which the vast majority of research shows weight loss is maintained long-term.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="faq-section">
  <h2 class="section-title">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq-item">
    <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">How long does it realistically take to lose 5kg?</button>
    <div class="faq-a">With a sustainable 500 kcal/day deficit, losing 5 kg takes approximately 10 weeks. A more moderate 300 kcal/day deficit extends this to 14–16 weeks. Very rapid loss is possible short-term but usually includes water weight and increases risk of muscle loss. 10–12 weeks is a realistic, healthy timeline for most people.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="faq-item">
    <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What should I eat to lose 5kg?</button>
    <div class="faq-a">Focus on adequate protein (1.6–2g/kg/day) to preserve muscle, high-volume vegetables to manage hunger, and consistent calorie tracking to ensure you are in a deficit. Reducing ultra-processed foods, alcohol, and liquid calories typically accounts for a large portion of the needed calorie reduction without complex meal planning.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="faq-item">
    <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Is it safe to lose 5kg in one month?</button>
    <div class="faq-a">Losing 5 kg in one month requires a ~1,200 kcal/day deficit, which is extreme and not recommended without medical supervision. The initial 2–3 kg may come from water weight, but the remaining genuine fat loss at this rate carries risks of muscle loss, nutrient deficiencies, and hormonal disruption. 6–10 weeks is safer.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="faq-item">
    <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Why am I not losing weight despite cutting calories?</button>
    <div class="faq-a">The most common reasons are underestimating food intake (people are typically off by 20–40%), overestimating exercise calorie burn, insufficient protein leading to muscle loss that lowers metabolic rate, inadequate sleep elevating hunger hormones, or simply not being in as large a deficit as assumed. Accurate food weighing for one week usually reveals the answer.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="faq-item">
    <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Will I gain the weight back after losing 5kg?</button>
    <div class="faq-a">Not necessarily — people who lose weight gradually (0.5 kg/week) using sustainable dietary changes (rather than crash dieting) show better long-term maintenance. The key is transitioning from weight loss to maintenance mode: recalculating your TDEE at the new weight and eating at that level with the habits established during the loss phase.</div>
  </div>
</div>

